result.execSummary:
The defendant Roger A. Larson Jr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (10th or More), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: Outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If reconfined or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.
Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the roadways until properly licensed.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the agent.  

Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with extended supervision conditions.

Upon release from prison the defendant shall be fitted with a sobrietor device, and remain subject to the device until the agent determines it can be removed.

supervisions.notes: Concurrent with: same as prison sentence.

Per Statute 343.301(g) your operating privileges for operation of Class D vehicles will require that vehicles owned and/or driven by you be equipped with an ignition interlock device.  Must install a mandatory Ignition Interlock Device when defendant obtains an occupational license or regular license.  There is a $50 ignition interlock surcharge imposed.

Stipulation to factual basis.   Court finds defendant has made his plea, and waived constitutional rights, freely, voluntarily and intelligently.  Factual basis exists.  Find guilty of OWI 11th.  DA Fox speaks.  Recommends 4 years incarceration.  5 years extended supervision.   Attorney Poss agrees with State's recommendation.  Defendant elects to exercise his right to allocution.  Court orders:  Total sentence of 9 years, concurrent with the sentence he is now serving.  4 years initial confinement, 5 years of extended supervision.  DL revoked for 3 years.  IID required for 3 years.  Alcohol assessment and DSP.  ES conditions:    Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the roadways until properly licensed. Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with extended supervision conditions.
